               Their Reward.
               Diuers holy Saints, and graue Philosophers, haue vttered such
  Hyperboles of the shortnesse of our life, that without an Hyperbole, That which
  is to come, may in a manner bee counted as past. Seneca calls it a
  Point, and lesse than a Point. And a Point hath scarce any more being or
  duration, than what imagination or a thought will giue it. A smoke, a shadow,
  a vapour, and the like, lasts but a little while; all which, are accommodated
  to our life: But a Point indureth much lesse. And therefore Iob sayth,
  That the ioy of an Hypocrite is but a Point. And if this bee their recompence,
  Receperunt mercedem suam.
               
