  Nazianzen cals vs, The Riches of God▪ And this (saith he) we are to
  esteeme as a singular fauour, Quia nos pro diuitijs suis habet, That he
  will vouchsafe vs so much honor as to account vs his Riches. And we are
  not onely his Riches, but his Delight and Recreation: Et delitiae meae esse
  cum filijs hominum, I made it my pleasure, to remaine among the children of
  men: Though my head were rounded with Starres, and circled about with a
  Crowne of infinite Glorie; yet did I humble my thoughts as low as Man. And here
  are we to ponder on the particle Et: And if Kings haue a care of their
  Parkes, and make great reckoning of their Gardens and houses of pleasure, for
  that they are their entertainment and recreation; How much more ought God to
  esteeme of his Vine, holding it to bee his Riches, his Pleasure, and
  Delight?
            
            
