               The distrubution of the matter.
               AMongst
the rest of the Parables, this Parable is treated of; and is diuided into foure
parts:
            The first relates the resolution of an idle young fellow desirous
to see the world, and to haue his fathers leaue to trauell.
            The second, His vnaduised actions, lewd courses, lauish expences,
and the miseries that befell him thereupon.
            The third, The consideration of his own wretched estate, his
returning home to his fathers house all totter'd and torne, weake, and
hungerstarued.
            The fourth, His fathers kind reception of him, and the joy that he
took in this his lost sonne.
            This followes verie fitly that former Parable of the Vineyard:
            That being full of feare; this, of hope:
            That, of the rigour of justice; this, of the regalos of
mercie.
            That checkes a sinner in his sinnes; this spurs him on to
repentance.
            And these are those two Poles whereon the whole gouernement of God
dependeth.
            
