  forced to flye to the Persians, where King Xerxes receiued him with a
  great deale of honour. Bookes are so full of these examples, that it were an
  endlesse labour to relate them. That glorious Doctor Saint Ierome
  giues it as an aduice, That he who desires to bee famous, must forsake his owne
  Countrie. He that goes to Flanders, or to the Indies, after hee comes home is
  the better respected. Clement the Pope reporteth, That in the
  Primitiue Church the people would flock to the Sermon of a stranger. The fourth
