  extraordinary expences, layd taxe vpon taxe, and tribute vpon tribute vpon his
  subiects, and dying in the end very poore, he left the reuenewes of his Crowne
  so deepely indebted, that his sonne Rehoboam was inforced to impose
  new tributes and taxations, by which he came to loose ten parts of his
  Kingdome. The holy Prophet Ieremy noted this disorder in
  Eliakim King of Iuda, the sonne of Iosias, Thou
  alleadgest (saith hee) that the Maiestie Royall doth suffer want and
  necessitie; and that for this cause, thou oppressest the poore, the
  fatherlesse, and the widow. Thy father, was not he King as well as thou? Did
  not he maintaine the state and greatnesse of a King? Did he not affoord many
  fauours for the ease of his subiects? yet we doe not heare any complaint of
  his grinding of the faces of the poore, nor of his wringing and racking of his
  vassals.
               
