               The one, That Tribulation conserueth Vertue.
               The other, That God giues tribulation to his best friends, as a
  reward of their great and good seruices.
               Touching the former, In that earthly Paradise, Vertue was
  conserued in it's perfect rest and quiet, because the goods of the bodie did
  concurre with the goods of the soule. But this concord was broken through
  sinne; and then vertue, amidst it's ease and pleasure, liued in greater
  danger; but in it's tribulation, in greater securitie. Caietan saith,
  That the certainest and most assured signe that Vertues are such strangers
  here vpon earth, is, for that they haue need of so many materialls of
  persecutions for their preseruation. Fire being in it's own sphere, is solely
  by it selfe conserued without any fuell to maintaine it, or breath of aire to
  blow it: the like succeedeth with Vertue.
